1508–1588","1515–1593":"1515–1593","1518–1579":"1518–1579","1520–1595":"1520–1595","1456–1538":"1456–1538","1473":"1473","1593":"1593","1482":"1482","1579":"1579","1500":"1500","1456":"1456","1588":"1588","1478":"1478","1521":"1521","1543":"1543","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1595":"1595","1508":"1508","1518":"1518","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1537":"1537","Cradley, Herefordshire, England":"Cradley, Herefordshire, England","Chaceley, Gloucestershire, England":"Chaceley, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1475–1521":"1475–1521","1473–1549":"1473–1549","1482–1537":"1482–1537","1478–1543":"1478–1543","1508–1588":"1508–1588","1515–1593":"1515–1593","1518–1579":"1518–1579","1520–1595":"1520–1595","1456–1538":"1456–1538","1473":"1473","1593":"1593","1482":"1482","1579":"1579","1500":"1500","1456":"1456","1588":"1588","1478":"1478","1521":"1521","1543":"1543","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1595":"1595","1508":"1508","1518":"1518","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1537":"1537","Cradley, Herefordshire, England":"Cradley, Herefordshire, England","Chaceley, Gloucestershire, England":"Chaceley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Peche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: unexplained.","German: possibly a variant of   Pech   ‘pitch, tar’.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Peče</b> or of its Germanized form   Petsche  , which is also a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Pech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Manuel, Alvaro, Diego, Edelmira, Emilio, Francisco, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose Angel.  German Gerhard, Hans, Ilse, Lutz, Manfred, Wolf.","Czech and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Peche was born in 1475, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England as the daughter of John Peche. She married William Powell in 1500, in Halifax, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1521, in her hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1475–1521":"1475–1521","1473–1549":"1473–1549","1482–1537":"1482–1537","1478–1543":"1478–1543","1508–1588":"1508–1588","1515–1593":"1515–1593","1518–1579":"1518–